St George's Plateau, 1930 and 2023 Original photograph by Edward Chambre Hardman From Wikipedia Liverpool Cenotaph stands on St George's Plateau, to the east of St George's Hall in Liverpool, England. It was erected as a memorial to those who had fallen in the First World War. The dates of the Second World War were subsequently added. The cenotaph consists of a rectangular block of stone on a stone platform, with bronze, low-relief sculptures on the sides depicting marching troops and mourners. It was designed by Lionel Budden, with carving by Herbert Tyson Smith. Initially designated as a Grade II listed building, its status was raised to Grade I in 2013. History In 1926, a competition was held to create a memorial using public funds, with Charles Reilly, professor of architecture at the University of Liverpool, as assessor. There were 257 entrants; the winning, anonymised entry was by Reilly's assistant, Lionel Budden. The building contractors appointed were A. E. Bradley and Company, the sculptor was Herbert Tyson Smith, and his bronze sculptures were made at the foundry of the Morris-Singer Company. The cenotaph was unveiled at 11 am on 11 November 1930 by the 17th Earl of Derby. Following the end of the Second World War, the dates 1939 and 1945 were added. These were unveiled on Remembrance Sunday, 10 November 1946, by William G. Gregson, Lord Mayor of Liverpool. Description The cenotaph consists of a rectangular block of Stancliffe stone, with bronze relief statues on the sides, standing on a platform of Yorkshire Silex stone. The rectangular block is 35 feet (10.7 m) long and 11 feet (3.4 m) high, the length of the bronze panels is 31 feet (9.4 m), and the platform is 61 feet (18.6 m) long and 15 feet (4.6 m) deep. It is orientated northeast‚Äìsouthwest, in parallel with St George's Hall. The bronze relief on the northwest face, opposite the hall, depicts a stream of marching troops in the uniforms of the various armed forces. Above the panel is an inscription reading AS UNKNOWN AND YET WELL KNOWN AS DYING AND BEHOLD WE LIVE, and below, the inscription reads OUT OF THE NORTH PARTS A GREAT COMPANY AND A MIGHTY ARMY. On the southeast face, facing Lime Street station, the panel depicts mourners laying flowers and wreaths on a Stone of Remembrance, with rows of graves in a military cemetery behind them. Above the panel the inscription reads TO THE MEN OF LIVERPOOL WHO FELL IN THE GREAT WAR with an added inscription below it reads AND ALL WHO HAVE FALLEN IN CONFLICT SINCE. Under the panel is an inscription reading AND THE VICTORY THAT DAY WAS TURNED INTO MOURNING UNTO ALL THE PEOPLE. On the shorter northeast and southwest faces are circular bronze shields with the coat of arms of Liverpool and festoons, and the dates of the two wars. Appraisal Detail from bronze sculpture depicting mourners laying wreaths on the Stone of Remembrance The cenotaph was designated as a Grade II listed building on 28 June 1952. On 8 November 2013, the designation was raised to Grade I. The reasons given for the designation include its design context with its "impressive location" adjacent to St George's Hall. Also noted is the architectural interest of the cenotaph, with its horizontal lines forming a foil to the vertical columns of the hall. Referring to its sculptural interest, the citation states that the "sculptural work is exceptional and is arguably Tyson Smith's finest and most powerful work". The design is considered to have contemporary significance in that rather than using "allegory and heroic idealisation", it employs "powerful and modern realist portrayals". The quality of its craftsmanship is praised, and it is also to have group value in its location near other listed buildings. In the Pevsner Architectural Guides, Sharples expresses the opinion that "it is one of the most remarkable war memorials in the country".

Of all the 5 polytechnic approved on the same date by the former president Muhammad Buhari, Only FEDERAL POLYTECHNIC AYEDE OGBOMOSO has started so far. - - In line with the determination of his administration to make tertiary education more accessible to young Nigerians, former President Muhammadu Buhari, in 2021, just about two years ago, established the Federal Polytechnic, Ayede, in Ogo-Oluwa Local Government Area Of Ogbomoso Zone in Oyo state, alongside five other Polytechnics. The President thereafter approved the appointments of eminent Nigerians, seasoned administrators, and core professionals as management teams and members of the Governing Council for the institution. Moments after his historic appointment, the Rector, and his management team settled down to rigorous work, and as a visionary and focused leader with the political will towards making the institution envious of all, Dr. Abdul-hameed-led management commenced and concluded the recruitment process for various positions in academic and non-academic cadres. Even though the management team is not resting on its oars to ensure that the citadel of learning is growing daily, it would be placed on record that the Federal Polytechnic, Ayede, is becoming the fastest-growing among its contemporaries. The institution, after inspection by a team of inspectors from the National Board for Technical Education (NBTE), had successfully secured approval to run four courses while efforts are ongoing to secure approval for about fifteen more courses. The approved courses are Computer Engineering, Computer Science, Science Laboratory Technology, and Statistics respectively. In addition, Federal Polytechnic, Ayede (FEDPA), has not only completed admission processes and matriculated its 211 pioneer students but also commenced the first semester examinations at the Iresa-Pupa temporary site for the 2022/2023 academic session. Although, with these remarkable achievements, opinion molders and observers were of the view that the Dr. Abdul-hameed -led FEDPA management team has reached its crescendo, however, to the University of Ilorin trained electrical engineer, the only reward for success is continuous hard work. Even though we were granted only four programmes to commence with, none of the other five polytechnics has been granted a single one. So, when we say we are the fastest growing polytechnic, it is not as if I am being boastful, but saying this to encourage us that we as foundation staff of this institution, still have a lot to do, to improve at the present level ‚Äù. As a relationship expert, Dr. Abdul-hameed has enjoyed a worthwhile relationship and conflict-free administration, especially with the Governing Council, principal officers, staff, the institution‚Äôs stakeholders, and the host communities. It is indeed imperative to state that over these past two (2) years, the Polytechnic under Dr. Abdul-hameed‚Äôs focused leadership has witnessed reasonable growth, as his efforts have not only attracted remarkable development to Federal Polytechnic, Ayede (FEDPA) using his networks and influence but has also opened up the fledging institution to great opportunities in a few years to come. The Polytechnic has received various support including the donation of staff quarters by former Senator Ayo Adeseun, the donation of four blocks of classrooms and offices at the Iresa-Pupa temporary site, the donation of a 18 seater bus & about 96million naira for renovations of temporal site during our take off by Hon. Sunday Dare, former Minister for Youths and Sports and fortunately an indigene of Ogbomoso, in addition to the four vehicles procured by the management, comprising three Hilux pickups and one Toyota sixteen seater bus. Others are the donation of laptops among other office equipment worth six million naira by the Ogbomoso Consultative Council (OCC), led by a former military governor of Oyo and Ogun states, Maj. General Oladayo Popoola (retd.) and the Pivotal Club of Ogbomoso supported the institution‚Äôs ICT centre with the sum of one million naira (N1m) respectively. Despite the multifarious challenges confronting the institution, the two -years of Dr. Abdul-hameed‚Äôs led management, have been eventful as it has recorded several breakthroughs on many fronts. Walla Walla ‚Äì People of Many Waters A Sahaptin tribe who lived for centuries on the Columbia River Plateau in northeastern Oregon and southeastern Washington, their name is translated several ways but, most often, as ‚Äúmany waters.‚Äù While the people have their own distinct dialect, their language is closely related to the Nez Perce. The tribe included many groups and bands that were often referred to by their village names, such as Wallulapum and Chomnapum. A hunter-gatherer tribe, they lived in ‚Äútents‚Äù that were easy to move. However, their lodging differed from many other nomadic tribes, in that it was bigger and covered with tule mats rather than hides. Called a longhouse, it was made out of lodge poles much like a tepee, but was much longer, sometimes as much as 80 feet in length. Resembling a modern-day ‚ÄúA‚Äù frame house in appearance, the lodge poles were covered with mats made of tule, a plant that grows freely in the area along waterways. When the tribe moved, the mats were gathered and moved and the lodge poles left behind. Beginning in the early 1700s the Walla Walla people raised great herds of horses, making their lifestyle much easier as they gathered seasonal plants. They also traveled across the Rocky Mountains to trade dried roots and salmon to the Plains Indians for buffalo meat and hides. The people were first encountered by white travelers during the Lewis and Clark Expedition in 1805. The explorers were warmly welcomed by Chief Yellepit, whose village of about 15 lodges, was situated on the Columbia River near the mouth of the Walla Walla River. The communication between the two groups was made between a Shoshone woman who had been captured by the Walla Walla and the expedition‚Äôs guide and interpreter, Sacagawea, who was also of the Shoshone tribe. Though Yelleppit extended an offer to the expedition to stay with the village, Lewis and Clark were in a hurry to reach the Pacific Ocean. However, they promised to spend a few days on their return. In April 1806, as the explorers began to make their way back east, the expedition spent several days with the Walla Walla, during which time, gifts were exchanged and goods traded. Two of the items left by the expedition with the tribe was a peace medal engraved with a portrait of Thomas Jefferson and a small American flag. In their documentation, Lewis and Clark estimated the tribe‚Äôs numbers as 1,600; however, this probably included other bands now recognized as independent. The next non-native to encounter the Walla Walla people was a trader by the name of David Thompson of the Canadian-British North West Company, who arrived in 1811. About five miles upriver from Chief Yellepit‚Äôs village, he staked a pole with a note claiming the territory for the British Crown and declaring that the North West Company intended to build a trading post at the site. Continuing downriver, Thompson stopped at Yellepit‚Äôs village, where he discovered the American ‚Äúclaims‚Äù in the form of Yellepit‚Äôs flag and medal. Though neither Lewis and Clark or Thompson had much power to actually lay claim to the region, Yellepit was very supportive of the idea of Canadians setting up a trading post nearby. By 1855, thousands of settlers had arrived in the region along the Oregon Trail and there was an insatiable demand for land and resources by the emigrants. In response, the new Washington Territory governor Isaac Stevens began to heavily pressure the Walla Walla and other area tribes to sign treaties agreeing to give up land and move to reservations. In May and June 1855, Stevens, along with Joel Palmer, Superintendent of the Oregon Territory, enacted three treaties at the Walla Walla Council. The Walla Walla, the Umatilla, and the Cayuse tribes were coerced to move from 4,000,000 acres of tribal lands to a reservation in northeastern Oregon, which was eventually reduced down to 72,000 acres over time. Other treaties were also established at the council with the Yakama, Palouse, and other tribes. That same year, gold was discovered on the recently established Yakama reservation, and conflict erupted between encroaching white miners and tribes of the Plateau. Many tribes eventually united together under the leadership of Yakama chief Kamiakin, marking the start of the Yakima War. Though the Walla Walla were initially not involved in the conflict, they, along with the Umitilla and Cayuse were eventually pulled into it. Today, many Walla Walla live on the Confederated Tribes of the Umatilla Indian Reservation. The Walla Walla share the land and a governmental structure with the Cayuse and the Umatilla tribes as part of the Confederated Tribes of the Umatilla. The three bands were united as a single tribal government in 1949 when the tribal leaders adopted a Constitution and By-laws. The confederate tribes currently have an enrollment of over 2,800 tribal members. The reservation is located in the area Pendleton, Oregon, near the Blue Mountains.

üëë EDWARD LONGSHANKS ~ KING OF ENGLAND üëë . üëë Edward I was born sometime during the night of the 17/18th of June 1239, at the Palace of Westminster. He was the son of King Henry III and Eleanor of Provence. His father decided to name him Edward, in honour of Edward the Confessor. Edward had not been a popular name amongst the English aristocracy. üëë During young Edward‚Äôs childhood, his poor health was a massive concern. Despite this, as an adult he reached a rather imposing six foot two inches in height. This was extremely rare for the time, and earned him the nickname ‚ÄúLongshanks‚Äù, meaning ‚Äúlong legs‚Äù. üëë When Edward was fourteen years of age, his father made a political decision, to arrange a marriage between his son and thirteen year old Eleanor of Castile, the half-sister of King Alfonso X of Castile. On 1st November 1254 in Castile, Edward married Eleanor, a marriage that would end up producing sixteen children! Unfortunately, only five daughters reached adulthood and one son, the future Edward II. üëë Edward became well-known during his reign for his contributions to reform. He encompassed medieval kingship in all its forms, serving as an administrator, soldier and a man of religious conviction. During his reign, many statutes were passed, in order to deal with the many problems that had been identified. üëë One of the main ones included ‚ÄòThe First Statute of Westminster‚Äô in 1275 which codified many existing laws from the time of the Magna Carta. One of Edward I‚Äôs greatest legacies, is the birth of the English Parliament. Under his leadership, the meetings became increasingly frequent, amounting to around forty-six occasions during his thirty-five year reign. üëë Much of his motivation for developing a form of government in the way that he did, was based on raising the necessary funds, through taxation, in order to wage wars. Some of these included waring with neighbours across the Channel. France also happened to be a strong ally of Scotland - another thorn in Edward‚Äôs side. üëë The first part of his reign was dominated by his dealings with Wales. In response to small uprisings occurring in Wales, he decided to take the approach on launching a complete conquest. He invaded in 1277, defeated Llwelyn ap Gryffyd, the Welsh leader, and subsequently went about building castles, in order to secure and demonstrate his power in the region. üëë Any signs of uprising were met with further violence, eventually ending Welsh hopes for independence. The country came under complete English authority and by 1301, Edward‚Äôs son was named Prince of Wales, a tradition that persists to this day. üëë His approach to similar issues of self-governance in Scotland however, were not so easy to resolve. "On a beautiful afternoon in 1959, Coretta and I journeyed from our hotel in Beirut to take a plane for Jerusalem. The fact that most of the time human beings put the risk of nuclear war out of their minds because it is too painful does not alter the risk of such a war. If we assume that life is worth living, that man has a right to survive, then we must find an alternative. In a day when guided ballistic missiles carve highways of death through the stratosphere, no nation can claim victory in war. I knew that I could never again raise my voice against the violence of the oppressed in the ghettos without having first spoken clearly to the greatest purveyor of violence in the world today: my own government. Good morning First UMC! This is Pastor Todd, and I had hoped that my first post about our Bible Land journey would be a little different, but here we are. As I write this, our ship is stopped in the middle of the Mediterranean. Many of you might be aware already that the ongoing conflict between Israel and groups in Gaza - namely Hamas - have escalated unexpectedly. Given the speed and enormity of the attack from Gaza, we are unclear as to whether we will be able to port in Haifa tomorrow to begin our journey in the Holy Land. We are unclear as to whether we will continue this leg of our journey as planned, or whether there will be a reordering of our itinerary, or possibly some alternative to our itinerary. What I am positive about though is that we are all safe, and the authorities responsible for making these decisions are currently deliberating our next steps. Safety will always be the top priority. We will still make our journey to Egypt, to visit Ephesus, and to finish our time in Athens and Corinth. The three days in the Holy Land may or may not take place. It may be the order of our trip is altered. More than anything, I am positive of God‚Äôs reassuring hand on all of us. This morning, we had a great lecture about the Holy Land presented by Pastor Adam Hamilton. And while he spoke to us about the sites we would see and their significance, I am reminded now of the many friends I have made over the years in Israel proper and throughout the West Bank. I am saddened by the fear and uncertainty they must be experiencing at this very moment. While we worry about our trip being interrupted, many of them are fearing for their very lives and futures. So while I am certain you all are praying for those of us on our journey right now, please join me in praying for all of those affected by this latest turns of events in the Holy Land. I‚Äôll share a picture from my very first trip to the Holy Land that sums up my daily prayer for all of us and those throughout the Holy Land right now. God bless you all, and I‚Äôm looking forward to sharing with you our experiences and seeing you when we return!

YOUR LOVE LANGUAGE: ACTS OF SERVICE When your love language is Acts of Service, you shine your brightest by demonstrating your love through helpful actions. Here's what it looks like when you're at your best and potential trouble spots during conflicts or stress: At Your Best: ü•∞You excel in anticipating your partner's needs and going the extra mile to make their life easier and more comfortable. ü•∞You take pride in completing tasks that alleviate their burdens, whether it's preparing a favorite meal, handling chores, or offering assistance. ü•∞Your thoughtful actions consistently show your commitment, dedication, and love, creating a sense of security and appreciation in your relationship. ü•∞Your selflessness and willingness to serve make your partner feel cherished and valued. Trouble Spots During Conflict or Stress: üò¨ Overextending Yourself: In the pursuit of helping, you might take on too much, leading to exhaustion and potential burnout. üò¨ Expecting Reciprocity: You may unintentionally expect your partner to show love in the same way, causing disappointment if they have a different love language. üò¨ Miscommunication: During conflicts, your partner might perceive your acts of service as a way to avoid addressing underlying issues, which can lead to miscommunication. üò¨ Unspoken Expectations: Frustration can arise when your acts of service go unnoticed or unappreciated, leading to feelings of neglect. üò¨ Neglecting Verbal Affirmation: It's essential to remember that verbal communication is equally important. During stress or conflicts, make an effort to express your feelings verbally, too. In challenging times, remember to balance your acts of service with open communication. Address conflicts by actively listening to your partner's concerns and expressing your love verbally. By maintaining this balance, you can navigate stress and conflicts while continuing to demonstrate your love through meaningful actions.

The Irish Roots Of John Lennon John Lennon was born on 9 October 1940 in Liverpool, England. His paternal great-grandparents named Lennon came from Co. Down. His paternal grandmother Mary (Polly) Maguire came from Dublin. Her parents came from Wexford. John‚Äôs maternal Great-grandmother came from Tyrone. Two of his maternal great-grandparents were From Wales. His maternal grandfather was English. Liverpool was heavily Irish. It was flooded with refugees of The Great Hunger of the 1840s like John‚Äôs great-grandparents, and steadily afterward. The Merseyside area is said to have the highest concentration of people of Irish blood outside of Ireland itself. Lennon was always conscious of his Irish heritage, as were the other Beatles. For example, George Harrison's maternal grandfather came from Co. Wexford while Paul McCartney's maternal grandfather came from Co. Monaghan. Early in their career, the Beatles would vacation in Ireland. In 1967, Lennon purchased the island of Dorinish in Clew Bay, Co. Mayo. It was sold after his death with the ¬£30,000 proceeds being donated to an Irish children's charity. In the Beatles' 1964 movie "A Hard Day's Night", Lennon speaks volumes as he tells the character of Paul's Irish immigrant grandfather that instead of Liverpool, he should have gone to Boston, where he would have been treated with more respect. With the onset of the conflict in the north, his anger was awakened at the treatment of the Irish. This anger would show itself in his music. His 1972 album "Some Time In New York City" features not one, but two songs about Ireland. Click the links below to hear them. The song "The Luck Of The Irish" tells the overall story of brutal repression, hunger, mass emigration, partition. He tips his hat to the Irish community in Liverpool "the 'Pool". He questions what the British are doing in Ireland and calls them "brigands" and "bastards", who are guilty of genocide. On the album cover, which is in the style of a New York Times newspaper; the lyrics to all the songs are written, he is careful to point out that he wrote this song first (these two songs are the only ones that show dates). His wife Yoko Ono co-wrote and sang as a duet with him. Lennon pointed out that he wrote "Luck Of The Irish" first as if to emphasize that his feelings preceded the infamous massacre that inspired the other song-"Sunday Bloody Sunday". On January 30, 1972, a peaceful civil rights march protesting Internment-mass imprisonment without trial in Derry City was fired on by the British Army. Thirteen innocent protesters were killed, another died later of his wounds. In the song "Sunday Bloody Sunday", Lennon's familiar image as a peace activist is missing. Here he preaches vengeance and revolution. He emphasises the innocence of the victims and condemns Internment. He acknowledges "Free Derry". He re-iterates his opinion that the "kids" are often falsely blamed. The line about "Stormont bans our marches" leaves no doubt about what he considered himself. He calls the loyalists's ancestors "Anglo pigs and Scotties"; and suggests that they return to Britain if they will not join a United Ireland, because they are a minority on the island as a whole. He refers the the prison camps, such as Long Kesh as concentration camps. He mentions Falls Road in Belfast to stand for communities affected by the Troubles, and finally asserts Ireland's right to independence and unity while rejecting any notion of sectarianism towards Protestants-"Ireland for the Irish, not for London or for Rome". The song does show a depth of understanding of someone who followed the events closely. # ** ISTHMUS OF CHIGNECTO ** **---------------------------------------------------------------------** **----The name Chignecto i**s a European adaptation of the Mi‚Äôkmaw term for a much larger region, Siknikt or Sikniktuk, the drainage place, that extends from the Cobequid highlands to the eastern edge of the Wolastoq (Saint John) River drainage area, and north to the Baie de Chaleur. The isthmus, at the centre of that district, is a resource-rich marshland traversed by rivers and portage routes that link the Bay of Fundy to the Gulf of St. Lawrence, and further to major river routes leading to the interior of the continent. Siknikt is a large district of Mi‚Äôkma‚Äôki, with the isthmus at its centre, whereas what is currently called Chignecto is a small strip of land, the margins of two provinces bisected by a border first created by imperial competition in 1713. Much of the research, writing, and storytelling about this region have focused on the history of Chignecto as a point of division between French and British colonial claims, centering imperial perspectives, and thereby marginalizing the perspectives of those who lived there. There had been a significant Mi‚Äôkmaw presence at Chignecto for millennia when, in the seventeenth century, a small Acadian group started a settlement there. This group planted the seed of a community that would grow and spread over its eighty-year history, sharing Chignecto with existing and also growing Mi‚Äôkmaw communities. These communities managed a coexistence in this space without colonial administrative presence, creating a distinctly independent region, until the French-British conflict brought the story of the shared place to a crisis in the 1750s. -**---Existing archaeology** also bears witness to the mobility associated with Chignecto. Connected by the coastal and river routes , the Indigenous peoples of the region travelled throughout Mi‚Äôkma‚Äôki and had access to goods from throughout the region. In Chignecto they encountered other cultures over millennia, adopting or adapting technologies and exchanging goods.[ ](https://l.facebook.com/l.php?u=https%3A%2F%2Fjournals.lib.unb.ca%2Findex.php%2FJNBS%2Farticle%2Fdownload%2F32890%2F1882528135%3Finline%3D1%26fbclid%3DIwAR2yzR3nPz5-H2gHnsu3PnJG22JT9yBPF_6Jk3HEcy-LyFIjHeIN9aLc79c%23no16&h=AT1P9n8S4AevXfASMUyOagjBjsBAH-SsllEeCdPQq-MiCAgvPnVncDDKiJnDhj1Ina1fm4HMDoU-2L2sCcOnFGOlLbDzPoQgON3V8fFJMDtQTaxJ_8WgTUUm5qownncgOw&__tn__=-UK-R&c[0]=AT1vura_XLFksuPsB1YRnZKB-k1XqjMm8uLZ3XATblmqF_PX4UvWd1X7jgGDcmq3gHoPqqyT19YnwfobVOBCeLQODqTRIohI3NxgZEtb4DZW8GQh-KPpuy1asKOp9aBWmlNwBuLOB25bVJfOSUCiOC2ZZKNE7JVXZoS3-XnAqa8LYD-sFjUVe2Zl8lE48jB4fi5-OsA36y6vJQVfk8Dt880) In 1613, Father Pierre Biard observed in his early description of Acadia that the wealth of fish and wildlife at Chignecto made it possible for Mi‚Äôkmaw inhabitants there to lead a sedentary life, something he did not believe was true of other community locations in Mi‚Äôkma‚Äôki. Missionaries‚Äô census data from the seventeenth and eighteenth centuries confirm the presence of a significant and stable Mi‚Äôkmaw community in the Chignecto region, sometimes identified as being at Beaubassin others as *Missagoueche*.[ ](https://l.facebook.com/l.php?u=https%3A%2F%2Fjournals.lib.unb.ca%2Findex.php%2FJNBS%2Farticle%2Fdownload%2F32890%2F1882528135%3Finline%3D1%26fbclid%3DIwAR31SBLsbm3IBbXitaObeseMJYIKC9CP7TmU-I5gbFozXj8No5YTTPootEs%23no17&h=AT3_T1wkO4e3ncDjtg9KbTVBkNTzjtymrLST0nS3LXBzICYFC8wNFB-NgAZ1dDv_vFVTYQ3Yr5Q7VpcXNtytF45KXGB74AefAnMt8M8AKszyIwC2cI1PIDxM-QT5GHqIAA&__tn__=-UK-R&c[0]=AT1vura_XLFksuPsB1YRnZKB-k1XqjMm8uLZ3XATblmqF_PX4UvWd1X7jgGDcmq3gHoPqqyT19YnwfobVOBCeLQODqTRIohI3NxgZEtb4DZW8GQh-KPpuy1asKOp9aBWmlNwBuLOB25bVJfOSUCiOC2ZZKNE7JVXZoS3-XnAqa8LYD-sFjUVe2Zl8lE48jB4fi5-OsA36y6vJQVfk8Dt880) This existing community and its connectedness with the larger region formed part of the attraction for the project of settlement begun in the 1670s by the married couple Jacques Bourgeois and Jeanne Trahan, and their extended family, sons and daughters, and their spouses. #LifeClass Ministering : Pastor Jite Orimiono Topic: The husband as a leader Text: Ephesians 5:22-23, Luke 12:48 We are all called into leadership. That means responsibility, leadership is not about telling, it's about showing. Jesus Christ he was a servant leader, He led by example and taught His disciples how and what to do, they watched him pray. Leadership starts from the home, by showing and by doing. It is important to know that when you marry you become a husband leader One of the greatest problems that families have to contend with in the home is lack of leadership, it is the reason most marriages are breaking. How do you position yourself to be found? In your place of service. Where is your root? Where are you planted? Who are you submitting to? That's very important because when we talk about submission we only look at it from the perspective of the wife, submission is twofold. The wife is submitting to you; you must be submitting to a higher authority. It is important to emphasize that the family is the foundation of society and that's why it is important everybody has a part to play. To whom much is given, much is expected (Luke 12:48) Six P‚Äôs of marriage 1. Pattern: pattern is a model design, it is a prototype 2. Purpose: purpose is the reason for it 3. Protocol: It is procedure/guidelines that surround the institution of marriage 4. Process: process is a series of events that lead to an outcome 5. Personalities: If one of these two personalities is defective it affects the outcome, so it is essential that when you are choosing a partner you seek counsel, knowledge first. 6. Principles: that's the guiding laws If the purpose is not known, abuse is inevitable. A Leadership framework Leadership is a process, with objectives, motivation, trust, and integrity. If leadership is the process of influencing others through direction, inspiration, motivation to attain some identified objectives, so if it is marriage; What is your objective? There must be a goal. As a husband, everybody draws strength from you. You need to develop your muscles enough to want to carry another, marriage is a baptism, it's a baptism that's one of the dimensions of marriage. When you get married at the point where you take the vows, you are immersed into the other person. What leads to a lack of leadership in the home? 1. Wrong leadership style 2. Lack of your presence as a husband and a father 3. Those who avoid responsibility, and they relinquish their role to their wives. Two is better than one. What does it take to embody this leadership quality that is lacking in many homes? (Colossians 2:9) 1. You must lead by example 2. Check your lifestyle, your speech should be Godly and good. 3. Communication is very important How do you conduct yourself for your business? 1. Lead by example (John 13:15) 2. Be committed to moral principles. Marriage requires submission, services and sacrifice. Your Existence is for the benefit of the other person because your spouse is your number one priority. Be an example of honesty and humility and integrity in your business or in your home. Lead by loving, God loved us unconditionally. Dream and share the Family Vision. Seek knowledge before marriage not love. Set the tone for prayer and family devotion. Learn to de-escalate conflict. Create warmth and friendship if you want to be a husband leader. Lead by management. Be self-disciplined, learn how to rule your own house (1 Timothy 3:5) your house must be your priority. Marriage is about sacrifice. #SundayService #HOTRService #HouseOnTheRockPortHarcourt

TIPOLOGII UMANE Cei nascuti in zilele de 1, 6, 11, 16, 21, 26, 31 ‚Äì Tipologia A1 ‚Äì Curgere si apa Dintre toate tipologiile, oamenii A1 sunt cei care au viziunea cea mai calda si mai frumoasa asupra iubirii. Pentru ei insisi, intregul lor destin se rezuma la ‚Äúa iubi‚Äù, iar daca nu reusesc acest lucru se simt nefericiti, neimpliniti, traind cu sentimentul ca nu si-au atins menirea in viata. Se indragostesc de multe ori in viata, cu prea multa usurinta am putea spune, de fiecare data ca si cand ar fi prima si ultima oara, insa dezvolta relatii sentimentale de o natura neobisnuita, adesea furtunoase si intense. Au o natura prietenoasa si adora sa traiasca in mijlocul celorlalti, inconjurati de viata, de tumult, de agitatie si de complicatii. Sunt precum apa: dinamici, plini de viata, agili, se strecoara printre stanci si oameni si in ciuda obstacolelor reusesc cumva sa iasa la suprafata. Chiar daca nu realizeaza, au capacitatea de a-i modela pe ceilalti, contribuind la evolutia lor interioara. Sunt insa si schimbatori si uneori, in ciuda unor calitati remarcabile, prea umili, modesti si sensibili la gesturile si cuvintele celor din jur. Cei nascuti in zilele de 2, 7, 12, 17, 22, 27 ‚Äì Tipologia A2 ‚Äì Foc si visuri Oamenii A2 au visuri inalte, asteptari si cerinte de proportii cosmice de la ei insisi, iar viata lor intreaga se construieste in jurul implinirii ambitiilor si dorintelor lor secrete. S-au nascut sa se redescopere, sa se lase modelati si sa nu isi lase spiritul sa se stinga. Sunt perfectionisti innascuti si atunci cand vine vorba de ceea ce-si doresc rareori fac lucrurile pe jumatate. Oameni A2 sunt ca focul: spontani, minunati, puternici, creativi, dominanti pana la cotropire, crezand intens in propria putere, impunand respect si admiratie, dar totodata si teama. Nu multi sunt cei care le stau neconditionat in preajma fara a nu se simti folositi, manipulati, influentati chiar si la un nivel inconstient. Cu greu incredinteaza unei persoane, fie ea si prieten, increderea lor. Pot fi numiti oricum, numai naivi nu. Isi cunosc interesele si stiu sa puna in balanta atat aspectele pozitive cat si pe cele negative ale unei chestiuni. Iubirea si implinirea sentimentala ocupa un loc important in viata oamenilor A2, insa intotdeauna cautarea persoanei potrivite se aseamana prea mult cu cautarea perfectiunii. Iubirea le survine pe o cale mai anevoioasa si de multe ori constata cu tristete ca au iubit cu adevarat atunci cand relatia respectiva se afla la final. Este foarte posibil ca de-a lungul vietii sa dezvolte tendinta spre egoism, malitiozitate, insensibilitate si sa emita exigente prea mari de la partenerul de viata. Cei nascuti in zilele de 3, 8, 13, 18, 23, 28 ‚Äì Tipologia C3 ‚Äì Aer si libertate Oamenii C3 sunt nascuti sa fie liberi, sa-si exprime sentimentele, sa spuna deschis ceea ce gandesc, sa circule dupa bunul plac, sa calatoreasca, sa cunoasca, sa experimenteze dupa legile propriului arbitru, sa transmita mai departe cunostintele pe care le detin. De multe ori, idealurile lor de viata nu cunosc o reprezentare concreta si materiala, ci sunt simbolizate de alte persoane. Oamenii C3 sunt totodata extrem de pasionali si impulsivi si pot deveni dependenti de cei pe care ii iubesc, avand tendinta de a-i sufoca, de a-i absorbi spiritual. Chiar daca detin arta stapanirii si a controlarii emotiilor, uneori deciziile pe care le iau ii sperie pe cei din jur prin necunoscutul si controversele carora le dau nastere. Daca vrei sa te iubeasca, lasa-i liberi si nu le ingradi spiritul. Sunt facuti sa simta, sa vada, sa guste, sa se delecteze cu tot ce este mai frumos pe lumea aceasta, sa experimenteze senzatii si emotii supreme. Cu greu poti fi legati de un loc, insa daca isi gasesc aici rostul, dupa lungi peregrinari, se intorc de buna voie la ceea ce au lasat in urma. Cei nascuti in zilele de 4, 9, 14, 19, 24, 29 ‚Äì Tipologia D4 ‚Äì Pamant si stabilitate Oamenii D4 sunt precum pamantul -consistenti, vitali, esentiali pentru existenta celorlalti, stabili, exercitand un magnetism aparte, toleranti pana la extreme, cu o minte ascutita si patrunzatoare. Sunt oameni practici, calmi, pacifisti, echilibrati, cu un simt al judecatii si al ratiunii foarte bine dezvoltat, stapanindu-si emotiile si exteriorizandu-le doar in fata acelor persoane pe care le considera a avea o afinitate cu ei. Cred in prietenie, in stabilitatea ei si o plaseaza adesea asupra tuturor celorlalte relatii interumane. Sunt insa adesea greoi, prea cerebrali, lipsiti de spontaneitate, luand deciziile cu mintea si mai putin cu sufletul. Felul lor de a iubi este unul loial, stabilind relatii de lunga durata cu o persoana care le aduce liniste si armonie. Chiar daca vor iubi intens si se vor simti atrasi de o persoana cu o personalitate opusa lor, vor avea tendinta de a se retrage la primul semn de conflict sau neintelegere. Foarte probabil ca se vor sustrage dintr-o relatie prea pasionala sub pretextul ca nu este ceea ce isi doresc de la viata. (truncated)

Callie Eh, Malaysian / Swiss Photographer, born 1972 We are born of love, love is our mother 2022 Fine Art Photography Born and raised in Malaysia, currently based in Switzerland. Her travels have inspired her to capture life with photography. What started off as a hobby, capturing special moments of her time around new cities and environments eventually evolved into a career she never foresaw coming. This very passion drove her to use the camera to express and deliver narratives previously unseen and untold. For her, photography became more than a way of creating memories. Photography has been a tremendous support for Callie and It has been a refuge for Callie during difficult times and a safe space to explore a multitude of emotions concerning love, conflict, and hope. Callie‚Äôs works mostly refer to life ‚ÄúIn the moment‚Äù. She captures people to reveal honesty and express the authenticity of their individuality, heritage, and life. The raw power of her images makes us want to know more about the subjects, their life, and their personal stories. ARTIST STATEMENT For me photography was a life-saver. It picked me up at a difficult time in my life and I have not let it go ever since. Originally from Malaysia, I have lived in various countries and I am now based in Switzerland. Photography has changed my view of the world and has made me see things differently. I like to mix genres but my greatest photographic passion right now is documentary photography, inspired by my travels, the people I meet, the different cultures and the different ways of life.

Shika is an adorable 4 yo sable female Shepherd who was slightly underweight at 65 lbs. She has gained some weight and is perfect now. Found as a stray, we do not know the details of her upbringing. What we can say is that she holds no grudges about the past or worries about tomorrow, as she has an amazing talent to adapt to life around her. From day one, this gal was ready to make friends with people and other canines at a large social event (possibly she knew they were the guests of honor). Hustle and bustle of strangers do not seem to disturb her steady centered self. She readily accepted pets and adorations of her endearing floppy ear. The company of her co-foster (see Amaretto) helped her to make sense of the fun, but she did well on her own among a multitude of volunteers. Shika does very well when greeting other dogs and will try her best to maintain order and peace among her pack. Her demeanor with other canines is generally submissive with a touch of ‚Äúwanna play?‚Äù. Objects such as toys or nyla bones are objects to promote chase, but not a source of conflict among her trusted pack mates. Her energy is mid-level and she will opt to come inside often to rest, especially during the summer heat. This girl enjoys daily walks and is learning to keep a forward motion with the help of her canine cohorts. Other dogs peak her interest on the walk, but she does not display any reaction other than forgetting to continue forward. When it comes to car rides, she hesitates when loading in a vehicle but will accept assistance without protest. Once she is in the car, she lays calmly through the entire ride. Slowly this is improving as she learns this is likely a ticket to a fun-filled adventure! Shika settles like an angel in the home, often choosing to lay close to her human on the floor. She does have a mischievous desire to ‚Äòrearrange‚Äô personal belongings, such as shoes, clothes, or linens that happen to be lonely. If she discovers a laundry basket unattended, she will gladly help move some items to plain view, like to the hallway or outdoor lawn. Most often, she will leave them there quietly for you to retrieve‚Ä¶and fold. Shika is housebroken and is accustomed to using a dog door. She does well with the company of another dog if her foster mom is at work. At night, she willingly enters her crate where she sleeps quietly through the night. This is a special gal who makes very little demands and offers solid devoted companionship without a fuss. Cats and small critters unknown. Level 2

It highlights Mary's capacity to assist and guide believers through life's challenges as her intercession is especially powerful due to her closeness to her son, Jesus Christ. This title's historical importance is notably tied to the Battle of Lepanto in 1571 when Pope Pius V called on the faithful to seek Mary's intercession through the Rosary. The resulting victory was attributed to her, cementing the association of "Our Lady of Victory" with triumph over adversity. Throughout history, Mary has been a source of hope, courage, and divine help for those facing struggles, whether physical, spiritual, or moral. This title reminds us of Mary's unwavering support for her children. It symbolizes faith in her maternal care and her ability to lead us to victory, directing our hearts and prayers toward her Son, Jesus Christ, the ultimate source of triumph. "Our Lady of Victory" is a timeless reminder of the enduring devotion placed in Mary by countless Catholics.

Must-see castles in Germany. This country, rich in history and architecture, has some of the most beautiful castles in the world. Here is a selection of 6 castles that you must visit.

1. Neuschwanstein Castle: Located in the picturesque Bavarian Alps, Neuschwanstein Castle is a fairytale-like structure that has inspired countless works of art, including the design of the Disney castle.

2. Eltz Castle: Perched on a hilltop in the lush Eifel region, Eltz Castle is one of the few castles in Germany that has never been destroyed or damaged in war or conflict.

3. Cochem Castle: This beautiful castle is located in the charming town of Cochem, and its impressive architecture and rich history make it a must-see for any castle lover.

4. Albrechtsburg: One of the oldest castles in Germany, the Albrechtsburg is a magnificent example of Gothic architecture and is considered one of the most important historical structures in the country.

5. Lichtenstein Castle: This beautiful castle is a perfect example of neo-Gothic architecture, and its location above the picturesque landscape of the Swabian Alps makes it a popular destination for tourists.

6. Drachenburg Castle: This imposing castle, located just outside Bonn, was built in the 19th century and offers a breathtaking view of the Rhine Valley and surrounding countryside.

Which castle is your favorite?

And don't forget to share with a castle-loving friend.

To be clear: This does not mean we let kids "run wild" with zero structure, boundaries, or guidance from a well-regulated adult. I'm not saying we don't step in and offer the appropriate support and values-based rules to help our children treat themselves and others with care and respect. 

What I am saying is the foundation for all of this starts with us. If we can't regulate ourselves in the heat of the moment or in the midst of conflict, how can we expect that of our kids? I have to remind myself of that all the time. It's SO hard. If it's hard for you, please know you're not alone. 

This is humbling work and some days it's really confusing and overwhelming. Deep breath. You are doing GREAT. You don't have to be perfect. We're all figuring it out as we go and I'm so grateful to be learning together in this wonderful community we've co-created.

Bombing is expected to intensify as Palestinian fighters have caused major damage to the Jewish state. In response to the strike by Palestinian fighters, Israel‚Äôs Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu has declared ‚Äúwar‚Äù.

In Gaza, people rushed to buy supplies in anticipation of days of conflict ahead. Some evacuated their homes and headed for shelters.

The Israeli government has confirmed that the number of Israelis killed has risen to at least 40. Several Israelis are captured and taken to Gaza.

Meanwhile Hamas deputy chief Saleh al-Arouri said the group is ready for ‚Äúthe worst case scenario‚Äù.

‚ÄúAll scenarios are now possible and we are ready for an [Israeli] land invasion,‚Äù he added.

He has told Al Jazeera that the group has captured ‚Äúa big number‚Äù of Israelis.

He said ‚Äúsenior officers‚Äù were among them.

On Saturday morning, Hamas fighters fired a barrage of rockets into Israel while launching an incursion from land, air and sea.

In the first three to four hours of the assault, dozens of Palestinians managed to reach deep into Israeli territory. They have captured a large number of Israeli soldiers, including commanders, and taken them back to Gaza. They have also taken over parts of Israeli towns near Gaza, as well as an important army base and other military facilities.

Following that, the Israeli army began a massive wave of air strikes targeting various parts of Gaza.

The death tolls on both sides are expected to rise and there are fears violence will spill into other parts of Israel and Palestine.

Arab countries, Saudi Arabia, Qatar and Oman has blamed Israel for the situation while most of the Western countries ensured all support for the Jewish state.

At least 198 people were killed in Gaza on Saturday, according to the health ministry in the Palestinian enclave, following a barrage of rockets fired into Israel by the Palestinian group Hamas, to which Israel responded with air strikes.

The ministry said up until 4:20 pm (1320 GMT) there were ‚Äú198 martyrs and 1,610 wounded with different injuries‚Äù in the conflict.

Earlier in the day, Hamas launched the biggest attack on Israel in years, killing at least 40 people in a surprise assault that combined gunmen penetrating into Israeli towns with a barrage of rockets fired from the Gaza Strip.

It‚Äôs always so meaningful to see someone you love shine out in the world, especially when their light touches others in deep ways too. 

El Abrazo (The Embrace) at Dia Chelsea. I could not be prouder of her. 

Without providing any instructions, her work invites us to slow down, speak with a soft voice‚Äîor refrain from speaking at all‚Äîand sharpen our senses so we can carefully notice what is immediately around us. Once I started to be reminded that I was a tiny particle of it all, it was impossible not to be profoundly moved. 
This reminded me of the magical day we spent with @ceciliavicuna (pictured here) accompanied by @bluegallo_keys at @organizmo_ last year. There were healing tears that day too as we honored the earth, our ancestors, and the important work done by so many land and water defenders, especially indigenous peoples.

Title: Through Blood and Dragons: Epic Fantasy (The Forged and The Fallen Book 1)
Author: R.M. Schultz

Rating: ‚≠êÔ∏è‚≠êÔ∏è‚≠êÔ∏è‚≠êÔ∏è‚≠êÔ∏è (5/5)

Through Blood and Dragons: Epic Fantasy, the first book in The Forged and The Fallen series by R.M. Schultz, is an enthralling and immersive journey into the world of Cimeren. With a captivating storyline, well-developed characters, and a richly detailed world, this book deserves a solid five-star rating.

The story takes place in a divided world, where a mysterious forest and the vast Lake on Fire separate the kingdoms. Chaos looms in the south as battles and quarrels between kingdoms escalate. In the midst of this turmoil, we follow the protagonist, Cyran Orendain, a squire of the dragonguard in the border outpost of Nevergrace.

Schultz masterfully portrays Cyran's emotional journey as he copes with personal loss and faces the challenges of his role. As the plot unfolds, secrets are revealed, and Cyran is drawn into a war that has been brewing for centuries. The concept of dragons as not only weapons but also engines of war adds a unique and intriguing aspect to the story.

The author's writing style is engaging and descriptive, effortlessly bringing the world of Cimeren to life. Schultz's attention to detail in crafting the settings, cultures, and political dynamics demonstrates a deep understanding of world-building. The pacing is well-balanced, keeping the reader hooked from start to finish.

The characters in Through Blood and Dragons are multi-dimensional and relatable. Cyran's growth and transformation throughout the narrative are beautifully portrayed, making him a compelling protagonist. The supporting cast also adds depth to the story, with their own arcs and motivations.

What truly sets this book apart is the sense of authenticity in the portrayal of emotions and the consequences of war. Schultz doesn't shy away from depicting the harsh realities of conflict, and the characters' vulnerability and resilience make the story all the more compelling.

Kerala‚Äôs Malabar region has a PR problem ‚Äî from Malappuram being called mini-Pakistan by Home Minister Amit Shah to Kannur being labelled one of India‚Äôs most politically violent districts. But in the last 10 years, Malabar has found new spokespersons. Directors, scriptwriters and producers are giving the region a makeover.

One of the biggest Malayalam hits of 2022, Thallumaala, is set in Malappuram. In the first fight of the film Wazim, played by Tovino Thomas is thrown into the mosque‚Äôs ablution tank, as the imam‚Äôs sermon plays in the background. The setting is undeniably Muslim, but the conflict is universal‚ÄîWasim placed his muddy shoes on the pristine white sneakers that belong to Jamshi, played by Lukman Avaran.

This blend of hyperlocal and universal has come to define Malayalam cinema‚Äôs new wave. Now there‚Äôs a new player on the block‚ÄîMalabar New Wave. The food, the language and the sartorial choices of Kerala‚Äôs Muslim-majority districts are now centre stage.

‚ÄúThere are two things that define the Malabar region‚Äîthe love for football and food,‚Äù says Zakariya. His debut film Sudani From Nigeria revolves around sevens football.

The Malabar region of Kerala‚ÄîPalakkad, Malappuram, Kozhikode, Kannur, Kasargod, and Wayanad‚Äîhas the highest concentration of Muslims in the state. From Hijab to halal, bias to biryani, Islamophobia to identity, Malabar New Wave is a powerful antidote to The Kerala Story phenomenon. While the number of big releases can be counted on one‚Äôs fingers their impact has not just created a subculture but also disrupted the industry.

This triggers the cue for stress more than anything else. Do you know what it is? 

Uncertainty. 

Your nervous system's inability to mentally, emotionally, and physiologically know what to expect following triggers our systems into fight or flight more than anything else. 

The issue here is that our nervous system will directly avoid and complicate the solution to our pain through avoidance and disconnect. 

Why would it not? 

Face fear or pretend like it doesn't exist? 

Uhhh yes I'll take cookies and ice cream instead of that dry kale salad all day thank you. 

However, the short term relief that comes from avoiding has consequences. 

It's not like it just goes away, that problem compounds in the vacuum of the mind one theory to why is that we operate based upon "the negativity bias". 

This states that our nervous system learns more from negative experiences than positive ones. Survival of the fittest is also the survival of the fastest to adapt which means those who are easily triggered into stress, according to evolution, have an advantage. 

Or at least they did. 

Now that the ancient system holds back more businesses from success and people from purpose-driven lives than anything else. 

We avoid the cure for our own poisoning. 

But how is it that some days we can confront the fear and other days it seems impossible? 

Resources. 

Your system takes inventory on your mental, emotional and energetic resources. 

If you just ran a marathon then running another one is not something your system is interested in. (this included emotional marathons as well) 

Self-regulation systems to allow you to be in a state that allows you to confront fear and leverage the education that life's stressors are trying to give you is a sustainable path to relieving burnout, self-sabotage and more. 

Phase 1: get clarity around what you need to confront. 

Phase 2: Lean in. Community and accountability to the standards of a person you want to be are the best ways to support this. 

More videos on this coming soon!

this can look like:

-laughing at inappropriate jokes or remarks to ease the tension/make others comfortable. 

-fuming/holding resentment, avoiding healthy conflict/confrontation 

-self sacrificing, neglecting your own basic needs (physical and emotional)

-dissociating during conflict or uncomfortable social situations 

-not standing up for yourself 

-a lack of boundaries in relationships/codependency

-disordered eating

-people pleasing

-feeling uncomfortable when receiving

-feeling guilty when resting/experiencing pleasure

Life update: On July 14th, I was admitted into the hospital. Weeks leading up, I was extremely fatigued, thirsty, light headed, losing weight, getting headaches, anxious and sleep deprived. I didn‚Äôt piece two and two together with all my symptoms as many of them were related to other aspects of my life. ‚ÄúI‚Äôm tired, because I‚Äôm a student-athlete‚Äù, ‚ÄúI lost a lot of muscle because I had ankle surgery‚Äù or ‚Äúmy eyes are blurry because I am sitting at a screen all day‚Äù. When I returned to sport it was very difficult. I couldn‚Äôt go a single day without a 2 hour nap, my body was always cramping up, I would collapse doing a Kip cast handstand on bars and I barely got my double backs around on the tumble track. The day I was rushed into the hospital I had practice and lift and I couldn‚Äôt even pick up a 15 pound weight. I ran to the bathroom and ugly cried and sobbed, looking in the mirror, asking what was wrong with me. I blamed myself for not working hard enough and taking too much time off. After some blood work, I got a call from my sportsmed doctor, she urgently told me to pack my bags and call my parents. She informed me that my blood sugar levels if normal should be between like 80-120 and that mine were well over 1,000. I was in utter shock. The next 24 hours were hectic and I was officially diagnosed with diabetes. I was relieved to know that I wasn‚Äôt crazy for the way I was feeling but also overwhelmed and scared for what my life was going to now look like. I didn‚Äôt think this year could get any worse. I thought I had already hit rock bottom like twice already lol. However, I serve a God who sustains me through it all. He turns all my what ifs to even ifs. Even if I take a pause from my sport, even if standing up for what‚Äôs right leads to conflict, even if my health is taken away, I can still find rest, peace and fulfillment. When God is all you have, He is all you need. I hope to continue to share my story so that you can be encouraged through your own struggles and find what your purpose here is :)

‚ÄúPeople don‚Äôt always show you their true colors when things are going their way, but you start seeing them for who they really are when your interests conflict with theirs, when you ask them to do something for you and they don‚Äôt, even though they promised they would, or when you suddenly start speaking up about what‚Äôs bothering you and they start attacking you instead of understanding where you‚Äôre come from. The truth is, you will never truly know someone or how much you mean to them until you disagree on something or until their loyalty is put to the test.

Because at the end of the day, their actions will always be a reflection of how they truly feel. Their actions will tell you the truth eventually; you don‚Äôt need to listen to their excuses and you don‚Äôt need to justify every little thing they do just to keep them in your life. When someone tells you they love you and they will never let you down, please don‚Äôt believe them unless they have proved that to you, because some people promise you the world only when it‚Äôs two feet away from them, and some people promise to stick with you till the end but then run away when you change the route.

So if someone‚Äôs actions don‚Äôt match their words, please believe their actions. Don‚Äôt make excuses for them. Don‚Äôt come up with stories to make yourself feel better. Don‚Äôt give them too many chances, because they will start taking you for granted and they will start losing respect for you. They will start believing that you‚Äôre okay with anything just because you don‚Äôt want to lose them. If you want your life to be more peaceful and less dramatic, start being okay with losing people who are okay with losing you and start seeing people for who they really are not who you want them to be.‚Äù

Writer: Sam Leslie @samleslie_2024 Media: Sofia Gevorgian @sofia_gevorgian The Komenda Wars may be the best example of the unfortunate repercussions of lengthy battles for supremacy and legitimacy. The conflict lasted from 1694-1700 and occurred in the Gold Coast (modern day Ghana), involving the Eguafo Kingdom and nearby African States. It concerned the Dutch West India Company (WIC) and British Royal African Company (RAC) trade rights. The conflict dictated the beginnings of a globalized world which, unfortunately, had drastically negative effects upon the region and its inhabitants. After the Komenda Wars, the Gold Coast became a Slave Coast. A Dutch slave trader, noted in 1705: ‚Äú[the Gold Coast] has already changed into a Slave Coast and‚Ä¶nowadays the natives no longer occupy themselves with the search for gold, but rather make war on each other to furnish slaves.‚Äù
As traffic near the port village of Komenda grew, hostilities surrounding the relationship between states emerged. In the Eguafo Kingdom, there were two main polities: great Komenda, the location of the royal capital, and small Komenda, the coastal village with various European factories otherwise known as a trading house or post. Although trade in gold proved viable before the 1680s, many European charters had yet to settle an outpost or factory for trade and gold mining in small Komenda. This changed when the WIC and RAC each rested their companies' fortunes on the viability of small Komenda while also working with the king of great Komenda. After the RAC abandoned their 7 year old factory in 1680, they returned in the fall of 1681. TEAMSTERS KICK OFF UNITY 2023 CONFERENCE IN BOSTON
Hundreds of #Teamsters gathered this morning in Boston to kick off the #Unity23 Conference. Tom Mari, President of Teamsters Boston Local 25 and Secretary-Treasurer of Joint Council 10, opened today's General Session by welcoming Teamster members and leaders from all over North America to the city of Boston.

Conference attendees heard from General President Sean M. O'Brien and General Secretary-Treasurer Fred Zuckerman along with Congressman Stephen F. Lynch, International Transport Workers' Federation @itfglobal General Secretary Steve Cotton, and Massachusetts Governor Maura Healey.

"We couldn't have won the contract we did at UPS without unity," O'Brien said. "Moving forward, we have to be united to take on the corporate bullies at UPS, Amazon, Delta, Anheuser-Busch, and others. The fight at UPS is never over. We are just getting started. Enforcing this contract at UPS is going to be key to organizing at Amazon."

"We are in a historic moment with strikes across the labor movement. The days of avoiding conflict are over. We have to take on these challenges head-on," O'Brien added.

"We need to organize in our core industries and negotiate the best contracts for our members," Zuckerman said. "That's what Sean and I have been focused on since we took office. We have good political leaders who have our backs, and we need more of them. If politicians aren't with us and all working Americans, we vote them out. It's not complicated."

"Twenty million transportation workers around the world know the Teamsters...The world stopped during the pandemic. Transportation workers didn't. We have to strive to improve workers' lives, but that's only possible with strong leadership and support from the rank-and-file," Cotton said.

"I am proud to be here standing alongside Sean O‚ÄôBrien, a leader from Massachusetts who now leads the national fight for the Teamsters. Sean never gives up fighting for working families. He's not afraid to be the underdog. We've been working together to take on bad corporate actors," Gov. Healey said.

The General Session continues this morning with more speakers. Stay tuned.

Today, I want to share with you a message from one of our team members who got drafted to the war this morning. It is a message that reminds us of the importance of empathy, solidarity, and the profound impact of world events on our lives.
This call to duty is a reminder of the sacrifices made by countless individuals in Israel, who stand ready to protect our homeland.

As a Jewish Moroccan woman, I am greatly affected by the significance of these events.
However, it is crucial to emphasize that our response to this situation is not about taking sides in a political conflict. It is about standing up for the fundamental human rights of the Israeli people who are facing unimaginable challenges right now. It is about acknowledging that innocent civilians, including children, families, and the elderly, have been affected by recent events.

Last night during one of our holidays, a cruel enemy attacked innocent civilians, resulting in the loss of lives and countless injuries. At least 700  people have lost their lives, and over 2600 others have been injured and this is probably underreporting. 

Our thoughts, prayers, and hearts go out to all those who have lost family members, as well as to those who are saying goodbye to their loved ones heading into a conflict zone, not knowing if they will return. 

We stand in solidarity of Israel. 
It is essential that we do not remain silent in the face of such suffering.
In these difficult moments, let us come together as a compassionate and understanding community. Let us offer our support, encouragement, and empathy to the people in Israel.

Israel‚Äôs Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu declared that the country was ‚Äúat war‚Äù on Saturday, after Palestinian militants in Gaza fired a deadly barrage of rockets and sent gunmen into Israeli territory in a major escalation of the long running conflict between the two sides.

The early-morning surprise attack has left at least 22 people dead and over 250 injured, according to Israel‚Äôs Magen David Adom (MDA) emergency rescue service. It comes on the 50th anniversary of the 1973 War in which Arab states blitzed Israel on Yom Kippur, the holiest day of the Jewish calendar.

Around 2,200 rockets were launched from the Gaza Strip into Israel on Saturday morning, according to the Israeli military, while armed gunmen infiltrated across the border in a ground assault into southern Israel.

Hamas, the Palestinian militant movement that runs Gaza and claimed responsibility for the attack, said it had captured several Israeli soldiers near the border after its fighters entered Israel by land, sea and air using paragliders.

Israel‚Äôs military has not confirmed reports of soldiers having been captured, but one video published by Reuters appeared to show Palestinian gunmen dragging an Israeli soldier out of a tank at the Gaza fence.

MDA also said that one of their ambulances had been taken into the Gaza Strip.

Dubbing the operation ‚ÄúAl-Aqsa Storm,‚Äù Hamas military commander Muhammad Al-Deif said in a recorded message that the group had ‚Äútargeted the enemy positions, airports and military positions with 5,000 rockets‚Äù and that the assault on Israel was a response to attacks on women, the desecration of the al-Aqsa mosque in Jerusalem and the ongoing siege of Gaza.

In response, the Israel Defense Forces (IDF) said it had launched strikes against a number of Hamas targets in Gaza, and said that it had issued a call-up of thousands of reservists.

Netanyahu has vowed that Hamas will ‚Äúpay a price it has never known‚Äù for the attack. ‚ÄúCitizens of Israel, we are at war ‚Äì not in an operation, not in rounds ‚Äì at war,‚Äù he said in a video message.

My book, Was It Even Abuse?, is written in four parts to support you in gaining clarity in keys areas of confusion and self-doubt after covert abuse.

Part one explores keys questions we ask ourselves:

*Was my relationship abusive?
*Why didnt i just leave?
*Do they do it on purpose?
*Am I the abusive one?
*Am I overreacting?

Part two explores:

*How the abuser builds tensions
*The impact of acute incidents of abuse
*The role of manipulation
*The effects of trauma bonding

*...And importantly, untangling your responses from being the cause of abuse to facilitate self-compassion and growth. 

Part three explores cognitive dissonance and:

*Our strong attachment to their potential
*Red flags, identifying abusive tendencies and reflections to empower yourself
*How the relationship shifts from the dream to the reality
*Why its hard to let go of the belief in their potential
*Reducing inner conflict, remaining strong in your truth and staying centered in the reality.

During both World War I and World War II, garlic was used for its medicinal properties to treat soldiers. In World War I, garlic was used as an antiseptic to clean wounds and prevent gangrene. It was dubbed "Russian Penicillin" during World War II because Russian soldiers, who were given garlic to prevent and treat various infections, had significant success in staying healthy on the battlefield. Garlic's natural antibacterial, antiviral, and antifungal properties made it an excellent choice for keeping soldiers healthy during these times of conflict. 

This historical use of garlic is one of the reasons it's still considered a superfood today, valued for its immune-boosting and health-promoting properties.

#REPOST @attwoodgarnett with @get__repost__app  From Passive to Assertive: Empowering Autistic Women

Many autistic individuals often find themselves facing unique challenges in their interpersonal relationships. This can lead to feelings of victimisation and, in some cases, even exploitation. In a recent study by Sarah Bargiela and colleagues (2016), participants shared their experiences, shedding light on the journey from passivity to assertiveness and the obstacles they encountered along the way.

** Please note that this post includes references to sexual abuse, which may be distressing to some readers; if you find such content distressing, please consider refraining from reading further. **

Passivity and Its Consequences:

Participants frequently linked their perceived passivity to their autism, highlighting how it had led to unhealthy relationships and high-risk situations. One participant expressed the pressure she felt to conform, stating, "I almost feel pressured by society to do it because you get told this is what is expected of you to make you be a good girlfriend, and you think, if I don't do it, then I am not fulfilling my duties." This struggle to please and appease others often left them feeling trapped.
Avoiding conflict was another common theme among participants. For many, any form of verbal disagreement was seen as 'having a fight.' This avoidance sometimes resulted in over-assertiveness, leading to damage in their friendships. As one participant put it, "When it finally comes out, I can be a bit too blunt." However, there were exceptions, with some women refusing to appease when they knew something was wrong.

A Shocking Incidence of Sexual Abuse:
Disturbingly, nine out of fourteen participants reported instances of sexual abuse. Half of these accounts occurred within relationships, where young women felt obliged or "gradually being pestered" into sexual activities. Arguments often escalated into sexual encounters, even when they didn't want to engage.

Cannons of The Lawrence School Sanawar

These two artillery pieces were presented as Trophies to the School by the Government of India in 1928 in recognition of the School's contribution to the Great World War of 1915-1918, and to honour the twenty-seven Sanawarians who fell in action during the conflict. These are early Turkish, 3.5", (13-pounder) breech-loading field guns reported to have been captured in 1916 in the Dardanelle during the Gallipoli Campaign. The guns with their carriages, were despatched from Ferozepore Arsenal on the 20th of March 1928, and after de-commissioning were installed in their present sites on the quadrangle in time for the opening ceremony of Birdwood School and unveiling of the Cenotaph in September 1929.

The guns remain standing there to this day, still overlooking the Cenotaph and Memorials below - silent sentinels to the memory of Sanawar's fallen.

Snow Leopard Conservancy, and our partners International Veterinary Outreach, Mountain Spirit, and Animal Nepal, recently hosted an eight day training program for Nepalese Junior Technicians and Junior Technical Assistants working in Manang District as part of the "One Health - One Wellbeing Animal Health & Conservation Training Workshop & Animal Health Clinics". 

The workshops were designed to strengthen local institutions to advance domestic animal health & welfare while mitigating human-wildlife conflict in the remote mountain communities of Nepal. 

Combining classroom based interactive learning with hands-on training, the workshop aimed to empower veterinary technicians who play a crucial role in promoting animal health & welfare as well as mitigating human-wildlife conflict in their communities to support coexistence with carnivores. 

During this training, we were able to provide preventative veterinary care for 250 domestic animals, reducing the threat of emerging zoonotic diseases spread to wildlife, particularly endangered snow leopards in Nepal. 

Very special thanks to our local and international partners @ivo.vets, @animal_nepal, Mountain Spirit and the rural municipalities within the Manang district of the Annapurna Conservation Area for making this possible! üêæ

üìªüì° The Conservation Hour radio shows are a regular feature on Mnkhanya Community Radio station (88.3 FM). Every Wednesday, between 5pm and 6pm, CSL, @zcp_zambia and @chipembelewildlife take turns to discuss topics that inform and engage the local community about conservation issues. Once a month, we all combine for a joint recap show. More than 50,000 listeners tune in each week, and have the opportunity to phone in and ask questions.
¬†
So far this year, CSL has presented shows about how farmers and chilli patrollers can work together, the annual Fun Run, farmer exchange visits, and recently, CSL‚Äôs quarterly human-wildlife coexistence meetings and the importance of stakeholder collaboration. Wide-scale messaging via radio is a valuable tool in helping communities understand how to safely prevent and reduce wildlife conflict.
¬†
Thank you @wwfzambia for funding the conservation radio shows.
¬†

Hi Phriends! I know it is super early but I have a 12 hours shift today and so no updates from me while at work to avoid any conflict.

Per disclaimer again, I 100% support Walgreens  employees to do this. 100% ! However, I am legally bound to say that I can‚Äôt ask anyone to walk out! Personal choice!

That being said, here is your process from the organizers. If you are a Walgreens employee and you want to participate, you can either ‚Äú call in sick‚Äù or you can literally walk out! That‚Äôs up to you! Simply, make sure that you are comfortable with your choice. While there is indeed unity in standing together and many employees have already chosen to participate, the organizers still want you to feel comfortable with your choice! 

Secondly, for the rest of us who want to support, we will do the same as KS. 

1) Keep sharing! Use #OperationSpotlight
2)wear colors : purple, black, blue and yellow for solidarity and support. Feel free to post on social media 
3)if you are brave, get in front of a Walgreens and snap a picture with your colors. I am so doing this!!! 
4) contact news station/ media outlet to get light on working conditions with emphasis again on patient safety ( always)!

If you are an association, I will suggest that you start working on your statement. Again, my advice to you is to please please stay away from repeating the same thing about PBMs and provider status! Simply show your support to those Walgreens employees by keeping your message about safety and culture! If you need examples, many state like VA, NY and CA  and KS took those stands! 

Thank you guys so much! I will keep everyone updated as I get information.

What a beautiful time to be alive and a pharmacist!

Seven chakra meditation is believed to have a positive impact on various aspects of our lives, including mindset, health, wealth, and relationships. Here's how it can help:

1. Mindset: Chakra meditation encourages self-awareness and mindfulness. It helps you connect with your inner self and understand your thoughts and emotions. This can lead to a more balanced and positive mindset, reducing stress, anxiety, and negativity.

2. Health: Each chakra is associated with specific areas of the body. By aligning and balancing these energy centers through meditation, you may experience improved physical and mental well-being. For example, heart chakra meditation can promote emotional healing and cardiovascular health.

3. Wealth: While chakra meditation may not directly bring material wealth, it can enhance your overall well-being and focus. A clear and balanced mind is more likely to make sound financial decisions, pursue opportunities, and manifest abundance by aligning your intentions with your actions.

4. Relationships: Chakra meditation can help you develop empathy and compassion, leading to healthier relationships. By working on your heart chakra, for instance, you may become more open and loving, improving your connections with others. Additionally, better self-awareness can lead to improved communication and conflict resolution skills.

Incorporating regular chakra meditation into your daily routine can have a holistic impact on your life, contributing to a positive mindset, improved health, a clearer path toward wealth-building, and healthier relationships. However, it's essential to remember that meditation is a complementary practice and should be combined with other positive habits for the best results.

October 7, 2023 
By Nidal al-Mughrabi and Maayan Lubell

REUTERS: The Palestinian Islamist group Hamas launched the biggest attack on Israel in years on Saturday in a surprise assault that combined gunmen crossing into several Israeli towns with a heavy barrage of rockets fired from the Gaza Strip.

As warning sirens wailed across southern and central Israel, including in Jerusalem, Israel‚Äôs military said it was on a war footing and the defence minister said the Iran-backed Hamas had made a ‚Äúgrave mistake‚Äù by declaring war on Israel.

The Israeli military said it had launched air strikes into Gaza, where witnesses reported hearing heavy explosions.

The attack marked an unprecedented infiltration by an unknown number of Hamas gunmen into Israel from Gaza, and one of the most serious escalations in the Israeli-Palestinian conflict in years. At least two Israelis were killed, Israel public broadcaster Kan reported. Medical officials said there were dozens of wounded.

Israeli media reported gunbattles between bands of Palestinian fighters and security forces in towns in southern Israel. Israel‚Äôs police chief said there ‚Äú21 active scenes‚Äù in southern Israel, indicating the extent of the attack.

In Gaza, people rushed to buy supplies in anticipation of days of conflict ahead. Some evacuated their homes and headed for shelters.

Hamas military commander Mohammad Deif announced the start of the operation in a broadcast on Hamas media, calling on Palestinians everywhere to fight.

‚ÄúThis is the day of the greatest battle to end the last occupation on earth,‚Äù he said, adding that 5,000 rockets had been launched.

The last major flare-up between Israel and Hamas was a 10-day war in 2021.

//Speaking in Code: Decoding Avoidant Responses//Q: ‚ÄúWhy won‚Äôt he repeat back what he understood when I‚Äôve expressed my feelings honestly?‚Äù
 
Conflict for individuals that have avoidant attachment is very difficult, because it‚Äôs historically been very threatening and unsafe. Conflict did not lead to resolution or deeper intimacy, instead it led to isolation, punishment, manipulation, or some kind of negative outcome.

Because of that, sharing a feeling feels very frightening. It can also feel like when you share your feelings, you‚Äôre accusing them of failure, already. That puts people‚Äôs defenses up.

Here are four possible reasons why it‚Äôs hard for him to respond to you, but there could be others.

1. He simply doesn‚Äôt have the language or emotional vocabulary.

2. He thinks you‚Äôre trying to emotionally manipulate him.

3. What you were expressing induces shame for him, and to articulate it out loud will intensify that experience.

4. What you are saying is very threatening, and so his mind and body lockdown in a dissociative trauma response.

If any of these apply, it will really depend on your partner‚Äôs individual experience.

I hope it helps!
