What I find amazing is that they didn‚Äôt learn from the past, and no quick reaction force to repel the attacks.
Though Israel is no stranger to terrorist attacks, Saturday‚Äôs assault was unprecedented ‚Äì not least because of the lack of warning. Israel‚Äôs military on Saturday found itself caught off-guard, despite decades in which the country became a technology powerhouse that boasts one of the world‚Äôs most impressive armed forces and a premier intelligence agency.

The questions for Israeli authorities are legion. It has been more than 17 years since an Israeli soldier was taken as a prisoner of war in an assault on Israeli territory. And Israel has not seen this kind of infiltration of military bases, towns and kibbutzim since town-by-town fighting in the 1948.

‚ÄúThe entire system failed. It‚Äôs not just one component. It‚Äôs the entire defense architecture that evidently failed to provide the necessary defense for Israeli civilians,‚Äù said Jonathan Conricus, a former international spokesman for the Israel Defense Forces.

Whether by coincidence or design, the attacks came the day after the 50-year anniversary of another unforeseen conflict, when a coalition of Arab states launched a surprise attack against Israel on Yom Kippur, the holiest day of the Jewish calendar, in 1973.

Since Israel withdrew from Gaza in 2005, it has spent billions of dollars securing the border from attacks. That has striking at any weapons fired from inside Gaza into Israel and stopping terrorists from trying to cross the border from air or underground using tunnels. To stop rocket attacks, Israel has used the Iron Dome, an effective rocket defense system developed with help from the United States.

Israel also spent hundreds of millions of dollars building a smart border system with sensors and subterranean walls that was, according to Reuters, completed at the end of 2021.

Israeli officials will almost certainly look at where those systems failed on Saturday. As of Saturday morning, Israel said Hamas had fired 2,200 rockets, though it did not release figures on how many of those were intercepted. Officials have not commented on if the border fence did its job.

''In this study, we show for the first time in a female teleost that non-breeding aggression depends on estrogen production. Gymnotus omarorum rely on short term estrogen synthesis to engage in territorial aggression, maintain high levels of aggression, and ultimately reach conflict resolution from which dominant/subordinate status emerges. Our results highlight the importance of fast acting estrogens in the control of non-breeding female aggression in G. omarorum.'' -Lucia Zubizarreta et al., 2020

Treatment with estradiol to animals and birds has been found to increase their aggression while aromatase inhibition has been shown to lower aggressive behavior. In the teleost fish G. oramorum, aromatase inhibition also significantly lowers aggression, as well as resolution of conflicts. In males, inhibition of aromatase leads to a failure to establish dominance after winning a bout. Aromatase levels are very high in teleost's. 

S. nigricans fish aggressively defend their territories year round and have low levels of circulation androgens, even after an aggressive conspecific interaction. Though suppressing androgen receptors does lower aggression in these fish, it could be due to decreased estrogen formation through androgen aromatization. 

Long term aromatase suppression in birds lowers aggression levels. With estradiol treatment their aggression levels return to normal (K.K. Soma, et al., 1999, 2000). 

Siberian hamsters are very aggressive during breeding season. They have low circulating levels of estrogen but their highly sensitized estrogen receptors allow for intense responses to estrogen. 

Activation of the anterior cingulate cortex (ACC) in rodents massively decreases their antisocial aggression, for example, it drastically reduces hostile biting. Contrarily, increased aggression is triggered by hypothalamus and/or amygdala activation. 

ACC activation stimulates the mediodorsal thalamus which is an area involved in behavioral flexibility, and lowers the activity of the basolateral amygdala, as well as the ventromedial and lateral hypothalamus. All of these areas are a part of the ''threat circuit'' neural network, involved in initiating aggression.

Interpretation:Polar bears are a species that live
in the Arctic, where they rely on ice covered waters to access seals, their primary source
of food. They also use sea ice to rest and breed. The polar bear is considered the largest
bear species on Earth. Unfortunately, they face numerous threats to their survival.
Climate change is the most significant threat, as melting sea ice reduces the polar bear's
access to food and habitat. Human polar bear conflicts have also increased as polar bears
search for food during the summer months. However, people are learning to adapt to the
polar bear's presence and take preventative measures to reduce the risk of conflict.
Additionally, the oil and gas industry's interest in the Arctic poses a significant threat to
polar bears' habitat, as oil exploration can lead to habitat destruction and oil spills that can
harm and even kill polar bears. Oil spills can also reduce the insulating effect of the bear's
fur and poison them if ingested. Unfortunately, the effects of climate change and human
activity have already had a devastating impact on polar bear populations. A recent study
found that the population of polar bears in northeast Alaska and the Northwest Territories
declined by 40 percent between 2001 and 2010 , from 1,500 to 900 bears.

Book review 
The Spanish Diplomats Secret by Nev March
Thank you to @netgalley and the publisher for an audio arc in exchange for my honest review. 
This was the first book I've read in the Captain Jim series. I think you can pick up the story from anywhere as this mystery was completely done on the ship itself. The only thing I missed out on was the relationship between Jim and his new wife Diana so I didn't know a lot about them or how they came to be together. I did like what we saw of their relationship, Diana did spend most of the voyage feeling seasick and just unwell in general so we mainly only saw Jim doing his detective work on his own until the last half of the book. Because of that Jim spent most of his time talking to several other people on the ship as he tried to find out what happened. Overall I did enjoy this story and found it interesting. I struggled to solve this mystery before Jim did which was nice for a change. We did get little hints and clues that were helpful, I just wasn't catching on to them because I was focused on a different character who I felt was acting suspicious. Some of my favorite parts of this story were ones where real history was woven into the story as it was talked about that America had a conflict with Spain about Cuba, and some other European power things were going on as well that were interesting to see be included in the story and how the passengers talked about it all. The narrator of this audiobook I enjoyed. The only part I did not like at times was some of the voices that were used for several of the women's side characters (one in particular reminded me of a TikTok voice changer sound and it got old rather quickly.) It was easy to tell who was talking in the story which was good since there were so many side characters who were important to the story. I do see myself potentially continuing with this series to break up some of the other series I am currently reading.

A treat to #spooktober with this collection of 7 stories and a title novella. I was intrigued for theme that was based on supernatural elements with our local multi-culture beliefs and myths; bit ghostly and slightly gore to me but loving most of the plot arcs and how each enthralled me with its tale on one‚Äôs desire, immorality, of loss and fears, vengeance, mystical atonement and dark secrets that lurking almost wickedly unsettling throughout the executions. 

I enjoyed the title novella, The Muse the most as it had a gripping dark adventure of an elderly editor who was trying to save his author from a series of a vengeful spirit‚Äî the backstory was intense with its sense of eeriness that hooked me till the end. A menacing plot for Feed The Boy with a toyol and its nightly hauls‚Äî of greed, regret and a black magic mess. Duke of Zhi amused me much with its fun storytelling, love the interactions and those unreal afterlife tour with the chinese myth demon. Spooky plot for Lullaby with a man who was tormented by his unborn child‚Äî disturbing suicidal scene yet I like the psychological part of it. Surreal and inventive execution for Sword of Angel‚Äî a dead dude gets reincarnated as a super assassin; so classy with an appealing chaos of its crime thriller scenes.

Loving the rest as much for the characterization also how few highlighted a riveting issue of paedophilia, psychological stress, familial conflict and one‚Äôs lifestyle in general. A recommendation for a short stories collection if you‚Äôre into supernatural theme and wanna go local. 4 stars to this!

Special thanks to the author @chuakokyee for sending me a copy of the book in return for my review!

The Israeli‚ÄìPalestinian conflict is one of the world's longest-running conflicts, with roots dating back to the late 19th century. The core of the conflict is the competing claims of Israelis and Palestinians to the same piece of land, the Holy Land.

Background

In 1947, the United Nations proposed a partition plan to divide the British Mandate of Palestine into two states, one Jewish and one Arab. The Jewish community accepted the plan, but the Arab community rejected it. In 1948, the State of Israel was declared, and the surrounding Arab countries launched a war to try to prevent its creation.

The war ended in 1949, with Israel in control of most of the territory of the former Mandate of Palestine. Hundreds of thousands of Palestinians were displaced during the war, and many fled to neighboring countries.

The current situation

Today, Israel controls the West Bank, the Gaza Strip, and East Jerusalem. The West Bank and Gaza Strip are considered to be Palestinian territories under international law, but Israel has maintained a military occupation of these territories for over 50 years.

The Palestinian people have limited self-government in the West Bank and Gaza Strip, but they are not sovereign. The Israeli government has built settlements in the West Bank, which are considered illegal under international law. These settlements have fragmented the West Bank and made it more difficult for the Palestinians to establish a viable state.

There have been numerous attempts to resolve the Israeli‚ÄìPalestinian conflict, but none have been successful. The most recent peace talks broke down in 2014.

The international community has generally supported the two-state solution, which would involve the creation of a Palestinian state alongside Israel. However, there are significant disagreements about how to achieve the two-state solution, such as the borders of the two states, the status of Jerusalem, and the right of return for Palestinian refugees.

By talkdiplomacy Writer: Sam Leslie ATsamleslie_2024 Media: Sofia Gevorgian ATsofia_gevorgian The Komenda Wars may be the best example of the unfortunate repercussions of lengthy battles for supremacy and legitimacy. The conflict lasted from 1694-1700 and occurred in the Gold Coast (modern day Ghana), involving the Eguafo Kingdom and nearby African States. It concerned the Dutch West India Company (WIC) and British Royal African Company (RAC) trade rights. The conflict dictated the beginnings of a globalized world which, unfortunately, had drastically negative effects upon the region and its inhabitants. After the Komenda Wars, the Gold Coast became a Slave Coast. A Dutch slave trader, noted in 1705: ‚Äú[the Gold Coast] has already changed into a Slave Coast and‚Ä¶nowadays the natives no longer occupy themselves with the search for gold, but rather make war on each other to furnish slaves.‚Äù
As traffic near the port village of Komenda grew, hostilities surrounding the relationship between states emerged. In the Eguafo Kingdom, there were two main polities: great Komenda, the location of the royal capital, and small Komenda, the coastal village with various European factories otherwise known as a trading house or post. Although trade in gold proved viable before the 1680s, many European charters had yet to settle an outpost or factory for trade and gold mining in small Komenda. This changed when the WIC and RAC each rested their companies' fortunes on the viability of small Komenda while also working with the king of great Komenda. After the RAC abandoned their 7 year old factory in 1680, they returned in the fall of 1681.
